You built a beautiful cedar deck five years ago. It looks gray now, boards are starting to splinter, and you're seeing soft spots in the rim board. You live on Vancouver Island and your neighbor's similar deck looks worse. Welcome to coastal home ownership.

The Island's climate is gorgeous but relentless. Salt spray, constant moisture, UV exposure, and violent storms combine to age wood faster than anywhere else in BC. Here's what happens and how to fight it.

## The Forces at Work

**Salt spray** — Oceanside, Qualicum Beach, and even Parksville get salt-laden air from the Strait. Salt particles settle on wood and accelerate oxidation and decay. Metal fasteners corrode in months instead of years. The salt also drives moisture deeper into the wood grain.

**Rainfall** — 1,400+ mm annually, mostly October–March. That's water sitting in wood constantly for half the year. Water penetrates grain, freezes (which expands and cracks), and creates ideal conditions for rot fungi.

**UV exposure** — The wood surface grays and checks (develops cracks). UV damage is mostly cosmetic at first, but it breaks down the wood cell structure and makes paint and stain fail faster. A gray deck isn't just old-looking; it's damaged.

**Temperature swings** — The Island's winter is mild (rarely below freezing for long), but freeze-thaw cycles still happen. Water in the wood freezes, cracks, and when it thaws, lets more water deeper in.

**Wind** — Storm-force winds push moisture into cracks and break fasteners. Broken fasteners allow movement, which opens gaps, which lets in more water.

## Why Decks Fail First

Decks have no walls and minimal overhang. They're fully exposed to all weather. Rim boards face downhill and collect water. Posts sit in soil or mulch, wicking ground moisture. Fasteners (bolts and screws) corrode. The ledger board—where the deck attaches to your house—is the most failure-prone spot. Water runs behind it, rots the rim joist, and invites carpenter ants.

Most Island decks fail at the ledger first. It's not visible, and by the time you notice, the rot is deep.

## The Failure Timeline

**Year 1–3:** Finish (stain/sealer) is good. Wood looks brand new.

**Year 3–5:** Finish starts to fail. Paint or stain flakes. Gray weathering appears. The wood surface is exposed to UV and moisture. No rot yet, but decay is starting.

**Year 5–8:** Boards start to soften (especially the rim board and outermost deck boards). The finish is gone. Water has penetrated the stain and into the grain. Soft spots mean rot inside.

**Year 8–12:** Visible rot. Splinters, spongy wood, boards start to fail. Posts may lean or settle. Ledger is compromised if not maintained.

**Year 12+:** Structural failure. The deck is dangerous and needs rebuild or removal.

This timeline assumes no maintenance. With maintenance, decks last 20+ years.

## Prevention Strategy

**The ledger is #1 priority** — This is where rot rots your house. The ledger needs flashing (an aluminum barrier with a drip edge that sheds water). Water must never run behind it. Every spring, inspect the rim joist below the ledger. If you see darkening or soft wood, that's rot starting. Fix it immediately.

**Slope the deck** — The deck should slope away from your house at a minimum of 1 inch per 100 inches of run (1:100 slope). This lets water run off instead of pooling. If your deck is flat or slopes toward the house, water sits and rots the wood.

**Keep gutters and downspouts clear** — Water from gutters runs down the fascia and pools on the deck. Clear gutters every spring and fall. Make sure downspouts drain away from the deck base.

**Seal the wood** — Apply sealer or stain every 2–3 years. This is non-negotiable on the Island. The sealer blocks water from penetrating the grain. It's cheap insurance; $500–$1,000 today beats a $15,000 rebuild later.

**Use the right materials** — Cedar is pretty but rots faster than pressure-treated (PT) lumber on the Island. PT lumber lasts longer but looks less pretty. Consider hybrid approaches: cedar decking for appearance, PT for structural elements (posts, beams, rim boards).

**Use stainless fasteners** — Regular steel screws and bolts corrode in 5–10 years. Stainless or hot-dipped galvanized fasteners resist salt spray. They cost more but last.

**Inspect the deck annually** — Walk it every spring. Look for:
  - Soft wood (poke with a screwdriver)
  - Stains or discoloration on the rim joist
  - Loose fasteners
  - Leaning or settling posts
  - Cracks in beams or rim boards
  - Rot at post bases (most common failure point)

Catch small problems early. A soft rim board costs $1,500 to fix. A fully rotted rim joist costs $5,000+.

**Trim branches overhead** — Branches drop leaves, debris, and shade. Shade keeps the deck wet; leaves clog gutters. Trim back anything hanging over the deck.

## Maintenance Schedule

**Spring (April–May):**
- Clean gutters and downspouts
- Inspect for winter damage
- Check ledger and rim joist
- Clear debris and mulch away from posts

**Summer (June–August):**
- Pressure wash (salt and grime buildup)
- Stain/seal if needed (dry season only)
- Inspect for new soft wood

**Fall (September–October):**
- Clean gutters before leaves drop
- Trim branches
- Inspect after storms

**Winter:**
- Monitor for ice dams (roof issues that affect gutters)
- Watch for water stains (roof or deck leaks)

## When to Repair vs. Replace

**Repair if:**
- Frame and posts are solid (no soft wood)
- Rot is localized (a few boards, one rim section)
- Ledger is intact

**Replace if:**
- Posts are rotten or leaning
- Rim joist is soft or missing
- Structural damage or bouncing
- More than 20% of the deck is rotted

A professional can assess. If you're uncertain, get an inspection.

## The Bottom Line

Coastal decks need maintenance. There's no getting around it. Spend $1,000 every few years on sealing and inspection, and your deck lasts 20+ years. Neglect it, and you'll replace it by year 10. On Vancouver Island, prevention is everything.

